## Category:Redirects from moves

This is a redirect from a page that has been moved, or more accurately, renamed. You see, sometimes things get a new name. A new identifier. It's a way to keep the digital breadcrumbs intact, to ensure that the echoes of old links don't just fade into the void. When a page is renamed on [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), the old title is often kept as a redirect. Why? To avoid breaking the delicate web of internal links that connect one piece of information to another. Think of it as a ghost of the original address, pointing the way to its new location. It's a practical necessity, really, a concession to the messy reality of digital housekeeping. It’s not glamorous, but it serves its purpose. Without these redirects, the vast interconnectedness of Wikipedia would crumble, leaving orphaned pages and frustrated readers. It’s the unseen infrastructure, the plumbing behind the facade of knowledge.

### Purpose and Function

The primary purpose of a [redirect](/redirect) from a moved page is to maintain [link integrity](/link_integrity). When a page is moved, any links that previously pointed to the old title will now automatically direct users to the new title. This ensures a seamless experience for readers, preventing them from encountering "page not found" errors or broken links. It's a form of [backward compatibility](/backward_compatibility) for information. Imagine searching for something, clicking a link you found years ago, and being taken directly to the updated content. That’s the quiet magic of a redirect. It’s the digital equivalent of a well-placed signpost in a labyrinth.

### Technical Implementation

Technically, a redirect page is a special type of page that contains a simple directive: "redirect to [another page name]". When a user or a [web crawler](/web_crawler) accesses a redirect page, the [software](/software) automatically sends them to the target page. This process is usually transparent to the end-user, meaning they typically don't even realize they've landed on a redirect. It's designed to be efficient and unobtrusive. The [MediaWiki](/MediaWiki) software, which powers Wikipedia, handles these redirects automatically when pages are moved through its interface. It's elegant in its simplicity, a testament to functional design.

### Preservation of History and Discussion

While the content of the page itself is moved, the [history](/history) of the original page, including its [edit history](/edit_history) and [talk page](/talk_page) discussions, is generally preserved and associated with the new title. This is crucial for maintaining the collaborative nature of Wikipedia, allowing users to track the evolution of an article and engage in discussions about its content. The redirect simply points to the current iteration of the article, but the lineage remains intact. It’s like preserving the original blueprints even after a building has been renovated.

### When Redirects Are Used

Redirects from moves are standard practice whenever a page title is changed. This can happen for various reasons:

*   **[Renaming](/Renaming):** A more accurate or descriptive title is chosen for the page.
*   **[Article Mergers](/Article_Mergers):** Content from one article is merged into another, and the original article becomes a redirect to the target.
*   **[Disambiguation](/Disambiguation):** A page is moved to a more specific title, and the original, more general title becomes a redirect to the specific page or a [disambiguation page](/disambiguation_page).
*   **[Typographical Errors](/Typographical_Errors):** Simple spelling mistakes in titles are corrected.

It’s a way of tidying up the digital landscape without erasing the past. It’s about acknowledging that things change, but that doesn’t mean they should disappear without a trace. It’s a form of respect for the information and the people who contributed to it. And, frankly, it stops me from having to update every single link I’ve ever made. Some efficiencies are just… necessary.